    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "Instructions\r\n----\r\nAn HR department is reviewing job applications and wants to compare the email addresses of two applicants to determine who submitted their application first alphabetically.\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #1:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">Job</code> class, complete the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">compareEmails()</code> method. This method should:\r\n\r\n- Use <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">compareTo()</code> to compare the two email addresses\r\n- Return the result of that comparison as an integer\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #2:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">JobRunner</code> class, create a <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">Job</code> object using two email addresses. Call the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">compareEmails()</code> method and print the result.\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #E0D1EC; border: 1px solid #9660bf; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1.1em; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">\r\n💡 <strong>TIP:</strong> <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">compareTo()</code> returns:\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>a negative number if the first email comes before the second</li>\r\n  <li>zero if the emails are equal</li>\r\n  <li>a positive number if the first email comes after the second</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n",
